  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much is a sargeant's retirement if he was in the army for 30 years?",
  "response": "The retirement pay for a Sergeant who served in the U.S. Army for 30 years would depend on several factors, including the Sergeant's base pay at the time of retirement and the retirement plan they are eligible for. \n\nUnder the traditional military retirement plan, known as the \"High-3\" retirement plan, a retiree receives 50% of their highest 36 months of basic pay after 20 years of service, with an additional 2.5% for each additional year of service. \n\nSo for a Sergeant with 30 years of service:\n\n1. 50% of the highest 36 months average basic pay for the first 20 years.\n2. Plus 2.5% for each additional year beyond 20 years (in this case, 10 additional years, which would be 10 * 2.5% = 25%).\n\nThis totals to 75% of the highest 36 months average basic pay.\n\nFor example, if the Sergeant's highest 36 months average basic pay was $4,000 per month, their retirement pay would be:\n\n$4,000 * 75% = $3,000 per month.\n\nPlease note that this calculation does not include any additional factors such as cost of living adjustments (COLAs), disability payments, or the impact of different retirement plans (like the newer Blended Retirement System). Also, the actual amount could vary based on the specific rank and time in service at retirement. It's always recommended to consult with a military pay or retirement specialist for a precise calculation.",
